                     In England, in the years 1654, 55, and 56. when our Climate was dryer than ever it had been mentioned to be in any Stories, ſo as we had very little Rain in Summer, or Snow in Winter, moſt of our Springs were dried up, ſuch as in the Memory of the eldeſt men living had never wanted Water, but were of thoſe Springs we call fontes perennes, or at leaſt were eſteemed ſo. He inſtances alſo out of a parallel Story out of Heylin's Geography, in the Deſcription of Cyprus, where the Author relates;
That in


the days of Conſtantine the Great, there was an exceeding long drought there, ſo as in Thirty Six Years they had no Rain, in ſo much as all the Springs and Torrents, or Rivers, were dried up; ſo that the Inhabitants were forced to forſake the Iſland, and to ſeek for new Habitations for want of freſh Water.
